        {
          "id": "medmcqa-b0f17b66-7fd5-48b4-b8eb-b2f5d595e58f",
          "text": "Which of the following is used as prophylaxis in case of diphtheria:",
          "options": [
            {
              "id": "opt-1",
              "text": "DPT vaccine"
            },
            {
              "id": "opt-2",
              "text": "Erythromycin"
            },
            {
              "id": "opt-3",
              "text": "Ampicillin"
            },
            {
              "id": "opt-4",
              "text": "DAT"
            }
          ],
          "correctOptionId": "opt-1",
          "explanation": "• In most countries, the diphtheria toxoid vaccine is given in combination with tetanus toxoid and pertussis vaccines (DTP vaccine).\n• DPT vaccine is most effectively used for prophylaxis and prevention of diphtheria.\n• Diphtheria is caused by the bacterium Corynebacterium diphtheriae. This germ produces a toxin that can harm or destroy human body tissues and organs.\n• One type of diphtheria affects the throat and sometimes the tonsils. Another type, more common in the tropics, causes ulcers on the skin.\n• Diphtheria affects people of all ages, but most often it strikes unimmunized children.\n• It is transmitted from person to person through close physical and respiratory contact.\n• DOC for Diphtheria infection: Erythromycin"
        }
