          "correctOptionId": "opt-3",
          "explanation": "The features noted are those of Vibrio cholerae, the causative organism of the severe diarrheal disease, cholera. The diarrhea is the result of the action of the cholera enterotoxin, which acts by ADP-ribosylating adenylate cyclase, leading to increased cyclic AMP with secondary increased efflux of Cl- and H2O. World-wide, cholera is usually spread by fecally contaminated water. Pseudomonas is an oxidase-positive, gram-negative rod that characteristically produces the blue pigment, pyocyanin. Salmonella is a motile, gram-negative rod that is a non-lactose fermenter that produces H2S. Shigella are non-motile gram-negative rods."
