          "explanation": "Klebsiella will be the probable cause of infection. With the above symptoms, the probable diagnosis is neonatal sepsis. Option 4 Klebsiella pneumoniae produces LF mucoid colonies on MacConkey agar (refer to the image below) and is among the common causes of neonatal septicemia. - Nonmotile, lactose fermenter (LF). - Capsulated, produce mucoid colonies. -Indole negative and Urease positive. -It causes pneumonia, UTI, abdominal, wound and surgical site infection. - K.ozaenae: It causes ozaenae (foul smelling nasal discharge)/atrophic rhinitis. Option 2 Hemophilus: Doesn't grow on MacConkey agar. Fastidious bacteria therefore, grows only on chocolate agar. Option 3 Strept. pneumoniae: Doesn't grow on MacConkey agar as it contains bile salts which inhibits the growth of gram positive cocci. Option 1 E. coli: LF and non mucoid colonies on MacConkey agar.",
